<li id="mwAjw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nawab_of_Oudh" title="Nawab of Oudh" id="mwAj0" class="mw-redirect">Nawabs of Oudh</a> (1722–1858 CE)</li>
<li id="mwAj4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nawab_of_Bengal" title="Nawab of Bengal" id="mwAj8" class="mw-redirect">Nawabs of Bengal</a> (1757–1880 CE)</li>
<li id="mwAkA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Talpur_dynasty" title="Talpur dynasty" id="mwAkE">Talpur dynasty</a> (1783–1843 CE)<sup about="#mwt1114" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-97" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-97"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-97" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 96;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[96]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAkI"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hunza_(princely_state)" title="Hunza (princely state)" id="mwAkM">Hunza (princely state)</a> (1500s–1974 CE)</li>
<li id="mwAkQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nagar_(princely_state)" title="Nagar (princely state)" id="mwAkU">Nagar (princely state)</a> (14th Century–1974 CE)</li></ul>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="29" id="mwAkY"><h2 id="South-East_Asia">South-East Asia</h2>
<ul id="mwAkc"><li id="mwAkg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Daya_Pasai" title="Daya Pasai" id="mwAkk" class="new">Daya Pasai</a> (1128–1285 CE).<sup about="#mwt369" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-98" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-98"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-98" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 97;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[97]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAko"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bandar_Kalibah" title="Bandar Kalibah" id="mwAks" class="new">Bandar Kalibah</a><sup about="#mwt372" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-99" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-99"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-99" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 98;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[98]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAkw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moira_Malaya" title="Moira Malaya" id="mwAk0" class="new">Moira Malaya</a><sup about="#mwt375" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-100" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-100"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-100" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 99;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[99]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAk4"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kanto_Kambar" title="Kanto Kambar" id="mwAk8" class="new">Kanto Kambar</a><sup about="#mwt378" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-101" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-101"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-101" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 100;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[100]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAlA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Robaromun" title="Robaromun" id="mwAlE" class="new">Robaromun</a><sup about="#mwt380" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-102" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-102"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-102" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 101;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[101]</span></a></sup></li></ul>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="30" id="mwAlI"><h2 id="East_Africa">East Africa</h2>
<ul id="mwAlM"><li id="mwAlQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kilwa_Sultanate" title="Kilwa Sultanate" id="mwAlU">Kilwa Sultanate</a> (957–1506 CE).<sup about="#mwt383" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-103" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-103"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-103" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 102;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[102]</span></a></sup></li></ul>

<section data-mw-section-id="31" id="mwAlY"><h3 id="Fatimid_caliphate">Fatimid caliphate</h3>
<ul id="mwAlc"><li id="mwAlg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fatimid_Caliphate" title="Fatimid Caliphate" id="mwAlk">Fatimids</a> (909–1171 CE): Controlled much of North Africa, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Levant" title="Levant" id="mwAlo">Levant</a>, parts of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arabian_Peninsula" title="Arabian Peninsula" id="mwAls">Arabia</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mecca" title="Mecca" id="mwAlw">Mecca</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Medina" title="Medina" id="mwAl0">Medina</a>. The group takes its name from Fatima, Muhammad's daughter, from whom they claim descent.</li>
<li id="mwAl4">In 909 CE the Shiite military leader <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abu_Abdallah_al-Shi'i" title="Abu Abdallah al-Shi'i" id="mwAl8">Abu Abdallah al-Shi'i</a>, overthrew the Sunni ruler in Northern Africa; which began the Fatimid regime.<sup about="#mwt1116" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-:0_104-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":":0"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-:0-104"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-:0-104" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 103;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[103]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAmA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jawhar_(general)" title="Jawhar (general)" id="mwAmE">Jawhar (general)</a> (<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arabic_language" title="Arabic language" about="#mwt389" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"lang-ar","href":"./Template:Lang-ar"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"جوهر"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAmI" class="mw-redirect">Arabic</a><span about="#mwt389">: </span><span lang="ar" dir="rtl" about="#mwt389">جوهر</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt389">‎</span><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_containing_Arabic-language_text" about="#mwt389" id="mwAmM"/>; <abbr title="floruit" about="#mwt390" typeof="mw:Transclusion mw:ExpandedAttrs" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"floruit","href":"./Template:Floruit"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAmQ">fl.</abbr> 966–d. 992) was a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fatimid_Caliphate" title="Fatimid Caliphate" id="mwAmU">Fatimid</a> general. Under the command of Caliph <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Al-Mu'izz_li-Din_Allah" title="Al-Mu'izz li-Din Allah" id="mwAmY">Al-Mu'izz</a>, he led the conquest of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./North_Africa" title="North Africa" id="mwAmc">North Africa</a> and then of Egypt,<sup about="#mwt1118" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-105" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-105"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-105" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 104;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[104]</span></a></sup> founded the city of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cairo" title="Cairo" id="mwAmg">Cairo</a><sup about="#mwt1120" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-106" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-106"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-106" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 105;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[105]</span></a></sup> and the great <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Al-Azhar_Mosque" title="Al-Azhar Mosque" id="mwAmk">al-Azhar Mosque</a>. A Greek slave by origin, he was freed by Al-Mu'izz.<sup about="#mwt1122" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-107" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-107"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-107" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 106;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[106]</span></a></sup></li></ul>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="32" id="mwAmo"><h3 id="Safavids">Safavids</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt394" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"main article","href":"./Template:Main_article"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Safavid dynasty"},"2":{"wt":"Safavid conversion of Iran to Shia Islam"},"3":{"wt":"Ideology of Safavids"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAms">Main articles: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safavid_dynasty" title="Safavid dynasty">Safavid dynasty</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safavid_conversion_of_Iran_to_Shia_Islam" title="Safavid conversion of Iran to Shia Islam">Safavid conversion of Iran to Shia Islam</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ideology_of_Safavids" title="Ideology of Safavids">Ideology of Safavids</a></div>

<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAmw"><a href="./File:Shah_esmaeil01.jpg" id="mwAm0"><img resource="./File:Shah_esmaeil01.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Shah_esmaeil01.jpg/220px-Shah_esmaeil01.jpg" data-file-width="450" data-file-height="600" data-file-type="bitmap" height="293" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Shah_esmaeil01.jpg/440px-Shah_esmaeil01.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/c/c3/Shah_esmaeil01.jpg/330px-Shah_esmaeil01.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAm4"/></a><figcaption id="mwAm8"> One of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shah" title="Shah" id="mwAnA">Shah</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ismail_I" title="Ismail I" id="mwAnE">Ismail I</a> of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safavid_dynasty" title="Safavid dynasty" id="mwAnI">Safavid dynasty</a> first actions, was the proclamation of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Twelver" title="Twelver" id="mwAnM">Twelver</a> sect of Shia Islam to be the official religion of his newly formed state. Causing sectarian tensions in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Middle_East" title="Middle East" id="mwAnQ">Middle East</a> when he destroyed the tombs of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abū_Ḥanīfa" title="Abū Ḥanīfa" id="mwAnU" class="mw-redirect">Abū Ḥanīfa</a> and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sufi" title="Sufi" id="mwAnY" class="mw-redirect">Sufi</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abdul_Qadir_Gilani" title="Abdul Qadir Gilani" id="mwAnc">Abdul Qadir Gilani</a> in 1508.<sup about="#mwt1141" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-108" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-108"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-108" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 107;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[107]</span></a></sup> In 1533, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ottoman_Empire" title="Ottoman Empire" id="mwAng">Ottomans</a>, upon their conquest of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Iraq" title="Iraq" id="mwAnk">Iraq</a>, rebuilt various important Sunni shrines.<sup about="#mwt1143" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-109" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-109"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-109" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 108;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[108]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAno">A major turning point in Shia history was the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safavid_dynasty" title="Safavid dynasty" id="mwAns">Safavid dynasty</a> (1501–1736) in Persia. This caused a number of changes in the Muslim world:</p>
<ul id="mwAnw"><li id="mwAn0">The ending of the relative mutual tolerance between Sunnis and Shias that existed from the time of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mongol_conquests" title="Mongol conquests" id="mwAn4" class="mw-redirect">Mongol conquests</a> onwards and the resurgence of antagonism between the two groups.</li>
<li id="mwAn8">Initial dependence of Shiite clerics on the state followed by the emergence of an independent body of <i id="mwAoA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ulama" title="Ulama" id="mwAoE">ulama</a></i> capable of taking a political stand different from official policies.<sup about="#mwt403" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-110" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-110"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-110" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 109;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[109]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAoI">The growth in importance of Iranian centers of religious learning and change from Twelver Shiism being a predominantly <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arab_people" title="Arab people" id="mwAoM" class="mw-redirect">Arab</a> phenomenon.<sup about="#mwt1106" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-111" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-111"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-111" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 110;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[110]</span></a></sup></li>
<li id="mwAoQ">The growth of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Akhbari" title="Akhbari" id="mwAoU">Akhbari</a> School which preached that only the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Qur'an_and_Sunnah" title="Qur'an and Sunnah" id="mwAoY" class="mw-redirect">Quran, hadith</a> are to be bases for verdicts, rejecting the use of reasoning.</li></ul>

<p id="mwAoc">With the fall of the Safavids, the state in Persia—including the state system of courts with government-appointed judges (<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Qadi" title="Qadi" id="mwAog">qadis</a>)—became much weaker. This gave the Sharia courts of <i id="mwAok"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mujtahid" title="Mujtahid" id="mwAoo" class="mw-redirect">mujtahids</a></i> an opportunity to fill the legal vacuum and enabled the ulama to assert their judicial authority. The Usuli School also increased in strength at this time.<sup about="#mwt1108" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-112" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-112"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-112" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 111;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[111]</span></a></sup></p>

<ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional" typeof="mw:Extension/gallery" about="#mwt1068" data-mw='{"name":"gallery","attrs":{},"body":{"extsrc":"\nThe declaration of Shi&apos;ism as the state religion of Iran by Shah Ismail -Safavids dynasty.jpeg|The declaration of Shiism as the state religion of the [[Safavid dynasty]] in [[Persia]].\nChaldiran Battlefield Site in 2004.JPG|Monument commemorating the [[Battle of Chaldiran]], where more than 7000 [[Muslim]]s of [[Shia]] and [[Sunni]] sects were killed in battle.\nFile:Battle of Chaldiran (1514).jpg|[[Battle of Chaldiran]], was a major sectarian crisis in the [[Middle East]].\n"}}' id="mwAos">
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:The_declaration_of_Shi'ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg"><img resource="./File:The_declaration_of_Shi'ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg/117px-The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg" data-file-width="997" data-file-height="1022" data-file-type="bitmap" height="120" width="117" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg/234px-The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg/176px-The_declaration_of_Shi%27ism_as_the_state_religion_of_Iran_by_Shah_Ismail_-Safavids_dynasty.jpeg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext">The declaration of Shiism as the state religion of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Safavid_dynasty" title="Safavid dynasty">Safavid dynasty</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Persia" title="Persia" class="mw-redirect">Persia</a>.</div></li>
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG"><img resource="./File:Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG/97px-Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG" data-file-width="861" data-file-height="1062" data-file-type="bitmap" height="120" width="97" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG/194px-Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b7/Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG/146px-Chaldiran_Battlefield_Site_in_2004.JPG 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext">Monument commemorating the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Chaldiran" title="Battle of Chaldiran">Battle of Chaldiran</a>, where more than 7000 <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muslim" title="Muslim" class="mw-redirect">Muslims</a> of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shia" title="Shia" class="mw-redirect">Shia</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sunni" title="Sunni" class="mw-redirect">Sunni</a> sects were killed in battle.</div></li>
<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px;"><div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Battle_of_Chaldiran_(1514).jpg"><img resource="./File:Battle_of_Chaldiran_(1514).jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg/106px-Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="901" data-file-type="bitmap" height="120" width="106" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg/213px-Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/73/Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg/160px-Battle_of_Chaldiran_%281514%29.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="gallerytext"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Chaldiran" title="Battle of Chaldiran">Battle of Chaldiran</a>, was a major sectarian crisis in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Middle_East" title="Middle East">Middle East</a>.</div></li>
</ul>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="33" id="mwAow"><h2 id="Community">Community</h2>

<section data-mw-section-id="34" id="mwAo0"><h3 id="Demographics">Demographics</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt407" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"main article","href":"./Template:Main_article"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"List of countries by Muslim population"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAo4">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./List_of_countries_by_Muslim_population" title="List of countries by Muslim population" class="mw-redirect">List of countries by Muslim population</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAo8"><a href="./File:Islam_by_country.png" id="mwApA"><img resource="./File:Islam_by_country.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Islam_by_country.png/400px-Islam_by_country.png" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="922" data-file-type="bitmap" height="184" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Islam_by_country.png/800px-Islam_by_country.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/31/Islam_by_country.png/600px-Islam_by_country.png 1.5x" id="mwApE"/></a><figcaption id="mwApI">Islam by country
<span style="background-color:#4a6600; color:white; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt408" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#4a6600"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApM"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span style="background-color:#a8e600; color:black; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt409" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#a8e600"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApQ"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span style="background-color:#f8ffe6; color:black; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt410" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#f8ffe6"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApU"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sunni_Islam" title="Sunni Islam" id="mwApY">Sunni</a>
<span style="background-color:#66004a; color:white; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt411" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#66004a"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApc"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span style="background-color:#cc0096; color:white; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt412" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#cc0096"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApg"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span><span style="background-color:#ffe6f8; color:black; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt413" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#ffe6f8"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApk"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span> Shias
<span style="background-color:#000000; color:white; border:1px solid #000000; text-align:center;" about="#mwt414" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"color box","href":"./Template:Color_box"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"#000000"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwApo"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ibadi" title="Ibadi" id="mwAps">Ibadi</a>
</figcaption></figure>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwApw"><a href="./File:Madhhab_Map3.png" id="mwAp0"><img resource="./File:Madhhab_Map3.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Madhhab_Map3.png/400px-Madhhab_Map3.png" data-file-width="1245" data-file-height="604" data-file-type="bitmap" height="194" width="400" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Madhhab_Map3.png/800px-Madhhab_Map3.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Madhhab_Map3.png/600px-Madhhab_Map3.png 1.5x" id="mwAp4"/></a><figcaption id="mwAp8">Distribution of Sunni and Shia branches of Islam</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAqA">According to Shia Muslims, one of the lingering problems in estimating Shia population is that unless Shia form a significant minority in a Muslim country, the entire population is often listed as Sunni. The reverse, however, has not held true, which may contribute to imprecise estimates of the size of each sect. For example, the 1926 rise of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./House_of_Saud" title="House of Saud" id="mwAqE">House of Saud</a> in Arabia brought official discrimination against Shia.<sup about="#mwt1124" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-saudi_113-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"saudi"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-saudi-113"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-saudi-113" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 112;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[112]</span></a></sup> Shiites are estimated to be 21% of the Muslim population in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./South_Asia" title="South Asia" id="mwAqI">South Asia</a>, although the total number is difficult to estimate due to that reason.<sup about="#mwt1110" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-114" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-114"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-114" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 113;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[113]</span></a></sup>
It is estimated that 15%<sup about="#mwt1126" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-CIA_115-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"CIA"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-CIA-115"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-CIA-115" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 114;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[114]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1128" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-BritannicaShiite1_116-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"BritannicaShiite1"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-BritannicaShiite1-116"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-BritannicaShiite1-116" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 115;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[115]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1130" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-PRC_117-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"PRC"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-PRC-117"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-PRC-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1145" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-mgmpPRC_118-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"mgmpPRC"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-mgmpPRC-118"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-mgmpPRC-118" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 117;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[117]</span></a></sup> of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Muslim_world" title="Muslim world" id="mwAqM">world's Muslims</a> are Shia. They may number up to 200 million as of 2009.<sup about="#mwt428" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-PRC_117-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"PRC"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-PRC-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAqQ">The Shia majority countries are <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islam_in_Iran" title="Islam in Iran" id="mwAqU">Iran</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islam_in_Iraq" title="Islam in Iraq" id="mwAqY">Iraq</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islam_in_Azerbaijan" title="Islam in Azerbaijan" id="mwAqc">Azerbaijan</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islam_in_Bahrain" title="Islam in Bahrain" id="mwAqg">Bahrain</a>.<sup about="#mwt1132" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-mafhoum1_119-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"mafhoum1"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-mafhoum1-119"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-mafhoum1-119" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 118;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[118]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1134" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-120" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-120"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-120" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 119;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[119]</span></a></sup> They also form the plurality (the largest group, but not the majority) in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lebanon" title="Lebanon" id="mwAqk">Lebanon</a>. Shias constitute 36.3% of entire local population and 38.6% of the local Muslim population of the Middle East including Iran.<sup about="#mwt1136" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-sha_121-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"sha"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-sha-121"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-sha-121" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 120;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[120]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAqo">Shia Muslims constitute 27-35% of the population in Lebanon, and as per some estimates from 35%<sup about="#mwt457" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-mafhoum1_119-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"mafhoum1"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-mafhoum1-119" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 118;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[118]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1239" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-122" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-122"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-122" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 121;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[121]</span></a></sup> to over 35–40% of the population in Yemen,<sup about="#mwt1241" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-123" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-123"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-123" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 122;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[122]</span></a></sup> 30%–35% of the citizen population in Kuwait (no figures exist for the non-citizen population),<sup about="#mwt1243" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-irfr2012_124-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"irfr2012"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-irfr2012-124"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-irfr2012-124" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 123;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[123]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1245" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-ssi_125-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"ssi"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-ssi-125"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-ssi-125" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 124;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[124]</span></a></sup> over 20% in Turkey,<sup about="#mwt459" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-PRC_117-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"PRC"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-PRC-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1267" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-126" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-126"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-126" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 125;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[125]</span></a></sup> 5–20% of the population in Pakistan,<sup about="#mwt1247" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-127" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-127"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-127" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 126;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[126]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt461" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-PRC_117-3" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"PRC"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-PRC-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup> and 10–19% of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shi'a_Islam_in_Afghanistan" title="Shi'a Islam in Afghanistan" id="mwAqs" class="mw-redirect">Afghanistan</a>'s population.<sup about="#mwt1249" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-lcweb2.loc.gov_128-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"lcweb2.loc.gov"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-lcweb2.loc.gov-128"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-lcweb2.loc.gov-128" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 127;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[127]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1251" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-CIAAFG_129-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"CIAAFG"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-CIAAFG-129"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-CIAAFG-129" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 128;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[128]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAqw">Saudi Arabia hosts a number of distinct Shia communities, including the Twelver <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bahrani_people" title="Bahrani people" id="mwAq0">Baharna</a> in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eastern_Province,_Saudi_Arabia" title="Eastern Province, Saudi Arabia" id="mwAq4">Eastern Province</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nakhawila" title="Nakhawila" id="mwAq8">Nakhawila</a> of Medina, and the Ismaili <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sulaymani" title="Sulaymani" id="mwArA">Sulaymani</a> and Zaidiyyah of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Najran" title="Najran" id="mwArE">Najran</a>. Estimations put the number of Shiite citizens at 2–4 million, accounting for roughly 15% of the local population.<sup about="#mwt1253" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-130" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-130"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-130" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 129;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[129]</span></a></sup> <link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:All_articles_lacking_reliable_references" about="#mwt468" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"better citation needed","href":"./Template:Better_citation_needed"},"params":{"date":{"wt":"October 2016"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwArI"/><link rel="mw:PageProp/Category" href="./Category:Articles_lacking_reliable_references_from_October_2016" about="#mwt468"/><sup class="noprint Inline-Template noprint noexcerpt Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;" about="#mwt468" id="mwArM"><span typeof="mw:Entity">[</span><i><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wikipedia:NOTRS" title="Wikipedia:NOTRS" class="mw-redirect"><span title="This claim needs references to better sources. (October 2016)">better<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>source<span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span>needed</span></a></i><span typeof="mw:Entity">]</span></sup></p>

<p id="mwArQ">Significant Shia communities exist in the coastal regions of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./West_Sumatra" title="West Sumatra" id="mwArU">West Sumatra</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aceh" title="Aceh" id="mwArY">Aceh</a> in Indonesia (see <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tabuik" title="Tabuik" id="mwArc">Tabuik</a>).<sup about="#mwt1269" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Leo_131-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Leo"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Leo-131"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-Leo-131" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 130;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[130]</span></a></sup> The Shia presence is negligible elsewhere in Southeast Asia, where Muslims are predominantly <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shafi'i" title="Shafi'i" id="mwArg" class="mw-redirect">Shafi'i</a> Sunnis.</p>

<p id="mwArk">A significant <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shi'a_Islam_in_Nigeria" title="Shi'a Islam in Nigeria" id="mwAro" class="mw-redirect">Shia minority is present in Nigeria</a>, made up of modern-era converts to a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Islamic_Movement_(Nigeria)" title="Islamic Movement (Nigeria)" id="mwArs">Shia movement</a> centered around <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kano_State" title="Kano State" id="mwArw">Kano</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sokoto_State" title="Sokoto State" id="mwAr0">Sokoto</a> states.<sup about="#mwt484" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-PRC_117-4" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"PRC"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-PRC-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt486" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-mgmpPRC_118-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"mgmpPRC"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-mgmpPRC-118" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 117;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[117]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt1271" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-132" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-132"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-132" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 131;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[131]</span></a></sup> Several African countries like Kenya,<sup about="#mwt1347" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Nairobi_133-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Nairobi"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Nairobi-133"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-Nairobi-133" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 132;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[132]</span></a></sup> South Africa,<sup about="#mwt1273" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-Matthée2008_134-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"Matthée2008"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-Matthée2008-134"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-Matthée2008-134" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 133;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[133]</span></a></sup> Somalia,<sup about="#mwt1349" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-135" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-135"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-135" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 134;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[134]</span></a></sup> etc. hold small minority populations of various Shia denominations, primarily descendants of immigrants from South Asia during the colonial period, such as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Khoja" title="Khoja" id="mwAr4">Khoja</a>.<sup about="#mwt1275" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-HaseMiyake2002_136-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"HaseMiyake2002"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-HaseMiyake2002-136"}}'><a href="./Shia_Islam#cite_note-HaseMiyake2002-136" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 135;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[135]</span></a></sup></p>

<section data-mw-section-id="35" id="mwAr8"><h4 id="Significant_populations_worldwide">Significant populations worldwide</h4>

<div class="PieChartTemplate thumb tleft" style="" about="#mwt487" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Pie chart\n","href":"./Template:Pie_chart"},"params":{"thumb":{"wt":"left"},"caption":{"wt":"Distribution of global Shia Muslim population among the continents"},"label1":{"wt":"Asia"},"value1":{"wt":"93.3"},"color1":{"wt":"Green"},"label2":{"wt":"Africa"},"value2":{"wt":"4.4"},"color2":{"wt":"Violet"},"label3":{"wt":"Europe"},"value3":{"wt":"1.5"},"color3":{"wt":"Red"},"label4":{"wt":"Americas"},"value4":{"wt":"0.7"},"color4":{"wt":"Blue"},"label5":{"wt":"Australia"},"value5":{"wt":"0.1"},"color5":{"wt":"Orange"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAsA"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px">
